  <p>Over the weekend of July 4-6, 2026, the World Cup reached its Round of 16, and the knockouts delivered what group football almost never does: matches that would not end on schedule. A tie level after 90 minutes now rolls into 30 minutes of extra time, and a tie still level after that is settled from the penalty spot. On the pitch, those extra minutes are the cruelest, most exhausting stretch of the tournament. On the betting app, they are something else entirely — a second window reopening on a game most bettors thought had already closed.</p>

  <p>We do not publish tips or picks, and this is not one. This is about a structural feature that the knockout format quietly hands the sportsbook: the live, in-play betting board stays open longer in a knockout than in any group game, and every extra minute it stays open is another minute over which the house margin is collected. The extra half-hour does not extend your edge. It extends your exposure — and it does so at the single most random, most emotional moment of the match.</p>

