  <h2>What the live board actually is</h2>

  <p>Live or in-play betting is the product the modern World Cup is built to sell, and we have set out how it works in our explainer on <a href="/articles/live-in-play-betting-explained-world-cup-2026.html">in-play betting as the tournament's core product</a>. In short: instead of one price set before kickoff, the sportsbook runs a board that reprices continuously as the game unfolds — next goal, next corner, the current result, the winning margin — offering a new decision every few seconds. Each of those prices carries the same thing a pre-match price does: a margin, the built-in gap between the odds offered and the true chance, which is how the book makes money regardless of who wins.</p>

  <p>The crucial point for the knockouts is not the margin's size on any single bet. It is the number of bets and the length of time the board is open. Live betting monetises turnover — how much money passes across the board — far more than any one outcome. A window that stays open longer, on a game that has more emotional pull, and reprices more often, is simply a bigger machine for turnover. Extra time is exactly that: the same machine, running an extra half-hour, at the moment a bettor is least able to walk away.</p>

